le (1479–1555), queen of Castile and its empire. Each of these women was perceived by their contemporaries as having gone "mad" as a result of excessive grief, and all three were related to Isabel the Catholic (1451–1504), queen of Castile and a woman lauded in her time as a paragon of reason.Through the lives and experiences of these royal women and the observations, judgments, and machinations of their families, entourages, and circles of writers, chronicles, courtiers, moralists, and physicians in their orbits, Silleras-Fernandez addresses critical questions about how royal women in Iberia were expected to behave, the affective standards to which they were held, and how perceptions about their emotional states influenced the way they were able to exercise power. More broadly, The Politics of Emotion details how the court cultures in medieval and early modern Castile and Portugal contributed to the development of new notions of emotional excess and mental illness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmotionsxSocial aspectsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMental illnessxSocial aspectsxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aWomenzIberian PeninsulaxSocial conditionsyTo 1500. 4aGENDER STUDIES. 4aLITERARY STUDIES. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aIberian Peninsula, queenship, depression, madness, gender in power, Spain, love in literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501773884?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501773884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501773884/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles